WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.369
Your music app just played you a song you love, by a band you have never heard of.

2
00:00:05.369 --> 00:00:09.428
Somewhere in a data center, two lists of numbers got compared,

3
00:00:09.428 --> 00:00:11.785
and the comparison said: same taste.

4
00:00:11.785 --> 00:00:14.208
So here is the question of the night.

5
00:00:14.208 --> 00:00:17.744
How do you score a match between two lists of numbers?

6
00:00:17.744 --> 00:00:18.988
Hold that question.

7
00:00:18.988 --> 00:00:22.523
One answer to it runs half of modern machine learning.

8
00:00:22.523 --> 00:00:23.520
Strip it down.

9
00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:27.008
A taste is an arrow: each direction is a quality,

10
00:00:27.008 --> 00:00:30.640
and the length is how hard the song leans that way.

11
00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:33.986
Take one probe arrow and four candidate arrows.

12
00:00:33.986 --> 00:00:36.620
Multiply them entry by entry and add.

13
00:00:36.620 --> 00:00:38.685
That single sum is the score.

14
00:00:38.685 --> 00:00:43.384
Before you drag anything, call it: which candidate ends up on top,

15
00:00:43.384 --> 00:00:45.591
and does any score go negative?

16
00:00:45.591 --> 00:00:48.795
Now turn the probe and watch the bars answer.

17
00:00:48.795 --> 00:00:51.785
Point at a candidate and its score climbs.

18
00:00:51.785 --> 00:00:53.352
Turn away and it dies.

19
00:00:53.352 --> 00:00:56.983
So a big score means two songs are the same, right?

20
00:00:56.983 --> 00:00:57.837
Watch again.

21
00:00:57.837 --> 00:01:01.753
The bars moved while the candidates never moved at all.

22
00:01:01.753 --> 00:01:05.526
The score reads agreement of direction, not sameness.

23
00:01:05.527 --> 00:01:08.148
Look at what your hands just learned.

24
00:01:08.148 --> 00:01:11.902
Point the probe along a candidate and the sum climbs.

25
00:01:11.902 --> 00:01:14.806
Point it across and the sum dies to zero.

26
00:01:14.806 --> 00:01:17.852
Point it against and the sum goes negative.

27
00:01:17.852 --> 00:01:22.173
One multiply and add, and it behaves like a meter with agree,

28
00:01:22.173 --> 00:01:24.369
ignore, and oppose on the dial.

29
00:01:24.369 --> 00:01:28.407
So say it plainly: the dot product is a similarity meter.

30
00:01:28.407 --> 00:01:30.319
Two lists of numbers go in.

31
00:01:30.319 --> 00:01:33.295
One honest reading of alignment comes out.

32
00:01:33.295 --> 00:01:39.103
And the reading tracks direction, because direction is all the sweep ever changed.

33
00:01:39.660 --> 00:01:41.217
Time to close the loop.

34
00:01:41.217 --> 00:01:44.467
Rebuild the meter from memory: two arrows go in,

35
00:01:44.467 --> 00:01:47.716
so what two operations turn them into the score?

36
00:01:47.716 --> 00:01:50.289
While you think, one more honest look.

37
00:01:50.289 --> 00:01:56.178
Stretch a candidate longer and its score climbs, even though its direction never moved.

38
00:01:56.178 --> 00:01:58.818
Long songs would win on sheer loudness.

39
00:01:58.818 --> 00:02:04.911
For the walk home: what is the cheapest fix that keeps the direction and forgets the size?

40
00:02:04.911 --> 00:02:05.611
Still up?

41
00:02:05.611 --> 00:02:08.499
The menu below has three ways to keep going.
